Pseudoaligment Explanation

I first pulled the rnaseq_assign file from Docker hub and found that the .gmt had been imported. From there, I used the exec command to run a container containing my rnaseq_assignment information. After that, I was able to index the homo_sapiens file that contains the data information for this assignment. Then I quantified the individual control and tumour samples to then be used in the rstudio server. I moved that data into the /home/rstudio/data area and created a sample.csv file containing that information.

When you enter the directory of the control and tumour files, the abundance.tsv file will contain the gene expression matrix.

I have implemented 6 Kallisto quantification directories and sample.csv file under /home/rstudio/data/ as well as a .gmt file.

tumour_dir = "/home/rstudio/rstudio/data"

Importing transcript-level abundances from kallisto in order to convert them to gene counts for downstream analyses using the differential expression analysis package in r (DEseq2).

Mapping the transcript IDs to gene IDs using the ensembl database.

mart = useMart(biomart = "ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")

DEseq2

Creating the DDS object for DEseq analysis that contains the metadata and helps form the model design for analysis. This specifies the colums of the metadata file and compares the control to the tumour data in the experiment.

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi, colData = samples, design = ~ replicate + condition )
## using counts and average transcript lengths from tximport

Adjusting the reference level to control in order to compare tumour vs control.

dds$condition <- relevel(dds$condition, ref = "control")
dds <- DESeq(dds)

Sample Heatmap distances matrix

Overview of the similarities and differences of the two samples

The color spectrum shows the number of differences between the two data samples for example, tumour_3 is very different than control_1, but control_2 is more similar to control_3.

# Calculate distance between samples
sampleDists = dist(t(rld_counts))

# Place distances in matrix
sampleDistMatrix = as.matrix(sampleDists)

# create annotation dataframe
ann = data.frame(Condition = samples$condition)

col = c("orange", "yellow")
names(col) = c("tumour", "control")
ann_col = list(Condition = col)

# match annotation rownames to distance mat
rownames(ann) = rownames(sampleDistMatrix)

pheatmap(mat=sampleDistMatrix,
         # pass distance metric calculated to heatmap
         clustering_distance_rows=sampleDists,
         clustering_distance_cols=sampleDists,
         # pass annotation dataframe 
         annotation_col = ann,
         # add colors
         annotation_colors = ann_col,
         # heatmap colours
         col=hcl.colors(100,"GnBu",rev=T))

PCA

PCA plots the variance of the samples in each principal component. The differential expression analysis shows that the closer together two sets of samples are together between PC1 and PC2 will provide less differentially expressed genes. Since the control samples are grouped together there is less differential expression, but the tumour samples have greater variation. The control samples have a positive correlation, while tumour samples have a negative correlation.

p = pca(rld_counts, metadata = samples)

biplot(p,
       colby = 'condition',
       colkey = c('tumour'='royalblue', 'control'='red1'),
       hline = 0,
       vline = 0,
       legendPosition = 'right',
       legendLabSize = 12,
       legendIconSize = 8.0,
       title = 'PCA bi-plot',
       subtitle = 'PC1 versus PC2')

Differential Expression Analysis

Extracting differential expression between phenotypes by applying the shrinkage estimator of low confidence differentially expressed genes toward zero. Since there are no outliers between the two samples, and the low confidence Deg are near zero, there are only a few genes that are differentially expressed between the tumour and control samples.

# make tumour vs control object
tumour_v_ctrl = results(dds, filterFun=ihw, alpha=0.05, c("condition", "tumour", "control"))
res1 = lfcShrink(dds=dds, res=tumour_v_ctrl, coef=4, type="apeglm")
## using 'apeglm' for LFC shrinkage. If used in published research, please cite:

Extract Up Expressed Gene Function

get_upregulated <- function(df){
    key <- intersect(rownames(df)[which(df$log2FoldChange>=1)], rownames(df)[which(df$pvalue<=0.05)])
  results <- as.data.frame((df)[which(rownames(df) %in% key),])
    return(results)
}

Extract Down Expressed Gene Function

get_upregulated <- function(df){
    key <- intersect(rownames(df)[which(df$log2FoldChange>=1)], rownames(df)[which(df$pvalue<=0.05)])
  results <- as.data.frame((df)[which(rownames(df) %in% key),])
    return(results)
}

Annotated Differentially Expressed Gene Function

get_downregulated <- function(df){
    key <- intersect(rownames(df)[which(df$log2FoldChange<=-1)], rownames(df)[which(df$pvalue<=0.05)])
    results <- as.data.frame((df)[which(rownames(df) %in% key),])
    return(results)
}

annotate_de_genes <- function(df){

    df$hgnc_symbol <- rownames(df)
    mart <- useMart(biomart = "ensembl", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")
    info <- getBM(attributes=c("hgnc_symbol",
                               "ensembl_gene_id_version",
                               "chromosome_name",
                               "start_position",
                               "end_position",
                               "strand",
                               "entrezgene_description"),
                  filters = c("hgnc_symbol"),
                  values = df$hgnc_symbol,
                  mart = mart,
                  useCache=FALSE)

    tmp <- merge(df, info, by="hgnc_symbol")
    tmp$strand <- gsub("-1", "-", tmp$strand)
    tmp$strand <- gsub("1", "+", tmp$strand)
    tmp$hgnc_symbol <- make.names(tmp$hgnc_symbol, unique = T)
    tmp <- tmp[!grepl("CHR", tmp$chromosome_name),]

    output_col <- c("Gene", "Ensembl ID", "Chromosome", "Start", "Stop", "Strand", "Description", "Log2FC", "P-value", "Adj P-value")
    tmp <- subset(tmp, select=c(hgnc_symbol, ensembl_gene_id_version, chromosome_name, start_position, end_position, strand, entrezgene_description, log2FoldChange, pvalue, padj))
    colnames(tmp) <- output_col

    if(min(tmp$Log2FC) > 0){
        tmp <- tmp[order(-tmp$Log2FC),]
    }else{
        tmp <- tmp[order(tmp$Log2FC),]
    }

    return(tmp)

}

Volcano Plot

Useful to show how many genes are differentially expressed in the tumour vs control samples. The most upregulated genes are shown on the right and the downregulated genes are on the left. Anything below the threshold line is known to be insignificant in gene expression between the tumour and control samples. Blue and red are significant gene expressions, but red are outliers for tumour effecting genes and therefore highly differentially expressed. The -log10P represents the p-values and the level of significance of each gene. The log2 fold change represents the difference between the levels of expression for each gene between the tumour and control samples.

## remove NA values from results
res1 = na.omit(res1)

## calculate min/max axis values for plot
min_width = min(res1$log2FoldChange)
max_width = max(res1$log2FoldChange)
max_height = -log10(min(res1[res1$pvalue>0, 5]))

## Grab top 10 up-reg genes for plot
up = subset(res1, res1$log2FoldChange > 1 & res1$pvalue <= 0.05)
up = up[order(-up$log2FoldChange),]
up_list = head(rownames(up), n=10L)

## Grab top 10 down-reg genes for plot
down = subset(res1, res1$log2FoldChange < -1 & res1$pvalue <= 0.05)
down = down[order(down$log2FoldChange),]
down_list = head(rownames(down), n=10L)

## place top 20 DE genes in vector (optinal...)
plot_top_20 = c(up_list, down_list)

EnhancedVolcano(res1,
                lab=rownames(res1),
                x="log2FoldChange",
                y="pvalue",
                selectLab=plot_top_20,
                drawConnectors=TRUE,
                legendPosition = "none",
                FCcutoff=1.0,
                pCutoff=0.05,
                title="Volcano Plot",
                subtitle="Tumour vs. Control",
                caption = paste0('Total Genes = ', nrow(res1)),
                xlim=c(min_width, max_width),
                ylim=c(0, max_height))

Heatmap

A way to show the differentially expressed genes of tumour vs control. The tumour and control samples are represented in the columns and the genes are represented in the rows. The colors represent the intensity of Deg in each sample with highly postive and highly negative correlations and therefore upregulated or downregulated.

##reset res1 for heatmaps
res1 <- na.omit(res1)

# subset the counts matrix to get the lung and control samples
subset <- rld_counts[, 1:6]

# now select de_up, de_down, i.e DE genes that passed the filtering our function produced
up <- rownames(de_up)
down <- rownames(de_down)

# subset matrix to include only DE genes
key <- c(up, down)
subset <- subset[which(rownames(subset) %in% key),]

# scale and center the values
mat <- as.matrix(scale(t(subset), center = T))

# basic plot to check we're plotting something sensible
#pheatmap(t(mat))

# spruce it up a bit..
ann <- data.frame(Condition = c(rep("Control", 3), rep("Tumour", 3)))
rownames(ann) <- rownames(mat)
col <- c("yellow", "orange")
names(col) <- c("Control", "Tumour")
ann_col <- list(Condition = col)

pheatmap(t(mat), 
         show_rownames = FALSE,
         annotation_col = ann,
         annotation_colors = ann_col,
         color = hcl.colors(100, "PRGn",rev=F))

Enrichment Plots

Pathways enriched in our tumour samples, and pathways enriched in Control

A positive enrichment score indicates gene set enrichment at the top of the ranked list and a negative enrichment score indicates gene set enrichment at the bottom of the ranked list. The larger the magnitudes of the enrichment score are better compared to rank. Gsea aims to decide if a gene set will happen towards the lower or top part of the gene list and used to assess how the genes of each gene set are distributed across the ranked list.

# Top DEGs Known Cancer Biology

ID2 is a known gene that can expressed in people with prostate and pancreatic cancer. This gene’s production is reactivated during the spread or metastasis of the tumour to surrounding organs from the primary tumour site. ID2 production mostly happens at the tumour site and can be expressed due to the repression of the semphorin 3F gene (a tumour suppressor in the placenta tissue). The semphorin 3F gene is overly expressed to inhibit the ability of tumour cells, such as ID2, to migrate and foster negative cancerous effects. As illustrated by the Volcano Plot, The ID2 gene is highly upregulated and must be highly downregulated by their suppressive counterparts during metastasis. [1]

SERPINA3 or Serpin Peptidase Inhibitor, clade A member 3 is a known gene that is downregulated and reduced in people who have lung cancer. It is known to be a biomarker for people with this type of cancer and allows for treatments, such as osimertinib to work more deligently and successfully when SERPINA3 is overly expressed. [2]

SERPINA3 upregulation has also been known as a highly expressed biomarker for patients who have Melanoma cancer. Over expression of the SERPINA3 gene has shown to correlate with the spreading of melanoma sites and invasion of melanoma cells in the tissue. It is said to be a factor in the progression of the radical growth phase to the vertical growth phase within the tissue of the epidermis. Studies show that an upregulation of the SERPINA3 gene is a biomarker for the survival of people diagnosed with melanoma cancer. As analysed in the Volcano plot, the SERPINA3 gene is upregulated and differentially expressed. [3]

ADAMTS12 or A Disintegrin and Metallopeptidase with Thrombospondin Type 1 Motif 12 is a known gene enzyme that is involved with gastric cancer. The gene is high expressed in gastric cancer tissues and upregulated, which indicates a biomarker that patients have poor survival rates. It was discovered, while using gsea analysis, that the gene may play a roll in the regulation of immune cell function and metabolism of human’s affected by gastric cancer. ADAMTS12 can be viewed as upregulated in the Volcano plot. [4]

HDAC9 is a known gene that can be expressed in people who have serous ovarian cancer. The gene is upregulated in people with serious ovarian cancer, which considers it a biomarker in the promotion of certain proteins that promote decreased survival rates. Additionally, research has show that people with non-serious ovarian cancer have highly upregulated HDAC9 and seem to have a higher survival rate. In the Volcano plot, the HDAC9 gene is downregulated and thus can be influential in people with non-serious ovarian cancer. HDAC9 inhibitors can be known as anticancer therapeutics when dealing with serious ovarian cancer. This gene promotes the cell migration of certain transcription factors that promote growth of tumour encouraging proteins. [5]

In conclusion, the affects certain differentially expressed genes have on the human body may promote tumour causing cancers. The use of different statistical methods may help scientists form inferences as to why certain genes may express regulatory factors. These regulatory factors are analysed using predictive and functional methods in r as illustrated by the tables and graphs above.
